qual and if there is at least one 'X'.\n4. If both conditions are satisfied, increment the count of valid submatrices.\n\nLet's implement this in Python:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def numberOfSubmatrices(self, grid: List[List[str]]) -> int:\n        m, n = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n        count = 0\n        \n        # Iterate over all possible submatrices starting from (0,0)\n        for i in range(m):\n            for j in range(n):\n                x_count = 0\n                y_count = 0\n                \n                # Iterate over the submatrix starting from (0,0) to (i,j)\n                for ii in range(i + 1):\n                    for jj in range(j + 1):\n                        if grid[ii][jj] == 'X':\n                            x_count += 1\n                        elif grid[ii][jj] == 'Y':\n                            y_count += 1\n                \n                # Check if the submatrix is valid\n                if x_count > 0 and x_count == y_count:\n                    count += 1\n        \n        return count\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- We iterate over all possible bottom-right corners of submatrices starting from (0,0).\n- For each submatrix, we count the occurrences of 'X' and 'Y'.\n- We check if the counts are equal and if there is at least one 'X'.\n- We increment the count of valid submatrices if the conditions are satisfied.\n\nThis solution has a time complexity of \\(O(m^2 \\cdot n^2)\\), which is acceptable given the constraints (up to \\(1000 \\times 1000\\)).", "estimated_date": 1720310400000}